00:45:31.600 --> 00:45:38.080
What types of automated tests or validation checks have you found most useful or most effective in

00:45:38.080 --> 00:45:43.919
catching those messier edge cases issues? I'm sorry if I read that wrong. Let me put it into

00:45:43.919 --> 00:45:54.479
the chat here. So if it's about messier edge cases that are hard to figure out, I would say

00:45:57.280 --> 00:46:05.280
I do remember a case where I was working on an app, and we knew what features are critical.

00:46:05.280 --> 00:46:08.959
So those need to work all the time, because otherwise the app makes no sense.

00:46:09.840 --> 00:46:16.719
And think of an e-commerce website, like the critical path is put something in the basket,

00:46:16.719 --> 00:46:23.120
go to checkout and buy it. So try to find that path for your app and set up an end-to-end test,

00:46:24.320 --> 00:46:33.199
for example, with ShinyTest2. And this might uncover some edge cases you might not anticipate.

00:46:33.199 --> 00:46:38.560
Like I do remember a case where I updated one package that was a dependency of a dependency,

00:46:38.719 --> 00:46:43.760
so I didn't even use it directly, but the test caught it because it broke

00:46:45.840 --> 00:46:50.399
part of this critical path. And the other is, yeah, use the deployment strategies because

00:46:50.399 --> 00:46:56.399
that's where you'll find those unknown unknowns. Of course, like other strategies that traditional

00:46:56.399 --> 00:47:02.080
ones also work, like ask for code review, like your teammate might figure out there's an edge case.

00:47:02.800 --> 00:47:11.439
