00:56:27.600 --> 00:56:32.959
Do you have any advice for testing these LLM categorizations? I'm thinking of use cases

00:56:32.959 --> 00:56:36.560
where there are no good data sets with existing categorizations

00:56:36.560 --> 00:56:39.520
or when our own classifications may be inconsistent.

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:50.560
This, I think, gets to kind of a crux of using LLMs for classification. But what I go to is I

00:56:50.560 --> 00:56:56.320
go back to like the gold standard of like testing for classification, which is that you should be

00:56:56.320 --> 00:57:04.959
testing on new data to see the, you know, the correct, like how the proportion of correct

00:57:04.959 --> 00:57:15.679
classifications to the incorrect ones. And when that's not possible, I think LLMs do allow for

00:57:15.679 --> 00:57:21.600
some flexibility, right? So we can use like uncertainty scores, looking at the, asking for

00:57:21.600 --> 00:57:27.840
the reasoning or the features it's looking at to understand what it's thinking. But when we have a

00:57:27.840 --> 00:57:32.560
lot of data, that's hard. So you might like sort through and just look at really all the cases

00:57:32.560 --> 00:57:38.239
where the LLM is uncertain, you know, maybe run some stats on that to see the mean uncertainty,

00:57:38.239 --> 00:57:45.360
the deviation, to understand like how difficult the LLM thought this task was, run that against

00:57:45.360 --> 00:57:50.719
our own expectations, you know, review some of those difficult to classify responses.

00:57:51.840 --> 00:57:57.840
Another technique you can use is you can use multiple LLMs as raters or different classifiers

00:57:58.800 --> 00:58:04.479
and try it that way to see if there are any disagreements or divergences in the different

00:58:04.479 --> 00:58:10.719
LLM models. I'd also look to see if there are existing machine learning models that are intended

00:58:10.719 --> 00:58:16.959
for your specific data, so they're trained on data just like yours. Now those might not be

00:58:16.959 --> 00:58:22.479
perfect either, but now you have multiple tools in your toolkit that you can start to use to converge

00:58:22.479 --> 00:58:28.800
on what a true response might mean if you don't feel like you can go through and make that

00:58:28.800 --> 00:58:34.000
determination for every single data point. Yeah, that's rough. Sometimes things are not mutually

00:58:34.000 --> 00:58:38.879
exclusive either. All right, thank you so much for that question and thanks Dylan for answering.

